'''= where users can connect their profile, friends and other data across multiple sites'''

[http://www.p2pfoundation.net/Social_Network_Site Social Networking Sites] are usually isolated silo's, so that individuals cannot port their relationships to other spaces. Distributed social networking aims to go beyond such limitations.


=Definition=

from Thomas Kalka at http://www.coforum.de/?6302:

"Sites like [[Videntity]] and [[Claim ID]] are now hooking
together [[Open ID]]  and [[Microformats]] to help provide for
the first distributed social networking schemes. These
are the seeds of something really exciting; the
ability to tie single sign-on with portable social
networking means we can quickly login to any site and
then pull our social networks along with us. Its going
to take time and quite a bit more work to get sites to
adopt a standardized means for doing this but its
inevitable now that OpenID is taking hold."


=Tools=

#The big Internet companies have initiatives such as [[Open Social]] [http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/opensocial_one_year_later.php] (Google), [[Facebook Connect]] [http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/facebook_connect_coming_soon_t.php], [[MySpace Data Availability]] [http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/myspace_data_availability.php], [[Yahoo Open Strategy]] [http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/yahoo_opens_yos_to_developers.php]. 
#There are also smaller company and open source projects such as [http://diso-project.org/ DiSo] and [http://noserub.com/ Noserub]

